L: 40.7–52.5 µm; W: 8.5–9.8 µm; DS: 11–13; VS: 10–12 (n=5).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="106" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,956,1307]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,294,992,1018]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Notes:—</emphasis>
These valves do not fit entirely 
<taxonomicName box="[640,753,992,1018]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Amphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="proteus">
<emphasis box="[640,753,992,1018]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">A. proteus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
since they usually have a single elongated areola on the ventral side, and not two rows of areolae as in 
<taxonomicName box="[573,687,1028,1054]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Amphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="proteus">
<emphasis box="[573,687,1028,1054]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">A. proteus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Schoeman, F. R. &amp; Archibald, R. E. M." box="[701,1032,1028,1054]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="425 - 437" refId="ref19126" refString="Schoeman, F. R. &amp; Archibald, R. E. M. (1986) Observations on Amphora species (Bacillariophyceae) in the British Museum (Natural History). V. Some species from the subgenus Amphora. Journal of South African Botany 52: 425 - 437. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / S 0254 - 6299 (16) 31507 - 1" type="journal article" year="1986">Schoeman &amp; Archibald 1986</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Levkov, Z." box="[1043,1195,1028,1054]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="1 - 916" refId="ref17095" refString="Levkov, Z. (2009) Amphora sensu lato. Diatoms of Europe 5: 1 - 916." type="journal article" year="2009">Levkov 2009</bibRefCitation>
), although a very short second row could be present (figs 2B–C), as in some of the valves of 
<taxonomicName box="[895,1008,1064,1090]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Amphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="proteus">
<emphasis box="[895,1008,1064,1090]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">A. proteus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Levkov, Z." box="[1041,1200,1064,1090]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="1 - 916" refId="ref17095" refString="Levkov, Z. (2009) Amphora sensu lato. Diatoms of Europe 5: 1 - 916." type="journal article" year="2009">Levkov (2009</bibRefCitation>
, Pl. 248: 6). Valves are also slightly smaller than those of the original 
<taxonomicName box="[648,761,1100,1126]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Amphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="proteus">
<emphasis box="[648,761,1100,1126]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">A. proteus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(length&gt; 50 µm, width&gt; 9 µm, 
<bibRefCitation author="Schoeman, F. R. &amp; Archibald, R. E. M." box="[1121,1447,1100,1126]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="425 - 437" refId="ref19126" refString="Schoeman, F. R. &amp; Archibald, R. E. M. (1986) Observations on Amphora species (Bacillariophyceae) in the British Museum (Natural History). V. Some species from the subgenus Amphora. Journal of South African Botany 52: 425 - 437. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / S 0254 - 6299 (16) 31507 - 1" type="journal article" year="1986">Schoeman &amp; Archibald 1986</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Levkov, Z." box="[136,289,1136,1162]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="1 - 916" refId="ref17095" refString="Levkov, Z. (2009) Amphora sensu lato. Diatoms of Europe 5: 1 - 916." type="journal article" year="2009">Levkov 2009</bibRefCitation>
). However, the only valve we were able to find under SEM (fig. 8D) showed the presence of dimple-like depressions internally near the elongated central nodule, as in 
<taxonomicName box="[843,958,1172,1198]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Amphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="proteus">
<emphasis box="[843,958,1172,1198]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">A. proteus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Levkov, Z." box="[974,1128,1172,1198]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="1 - 916" refId="ref17095" refString="Levkov, Z. (2009) Amphora sensu lato. Diatoms of Europe 5: 1 - 916." type="journal article" year="2009">Levkov 2009</bibRefCitation>
, Pl. 248: 6). Another similar taxon in both dimensions and striation pattern, 
<taxonomicName authority="Proshkina-Lavrenko" authorityName="Proshkina-Lavrenko" box="[670,1176,1208,1234]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" form="varians" genus="Amphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="form" species="proteoides">
<emphasis box="[670,820,1208,1234]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">A. proteoides</emphasis>
f. 
<emphasis box="[852,936,1209,1234]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">varians</emphasis>
Proshkina-Lavrenko
</taxonomicName>
, was described from the Black Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Proshkina-Lavrenko, A. I." box="[262,559,1244,1271]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" refId="ref18620" refString="Proshkina-Lavrenko, A. I. (1963) Diatoms from the Black Sea benthos. Akademii Nauk USSR, Moscow-Leningrad, 243 pp. [in Russian]" type="book" year="1963">Proshkina-Lavrenko 1963</bibRefCitation>
). Unfortunately, it is only known from her description and drawings (Proshkina-Lavrenko 1963, Pl. IX: 1–4), presenting insufficient details for species separation nowadays.
</paragraph>
